If you've done any of my workouts and made it to the end, you'll know that I use that stretching time to make some reflections. This quote is one that I have uttered for many, many years now. 

All of the micro-processes that you do on a daily basis add up. They are the dripping water on the stone! Your workouts, 5 minute meditations, meal prep, daily walks, staying hydrated, journaling, self talk, protein intake, and sleep are adding up.

These habits and routines are changing the trajectory of your health. It's not one giant step that will do it (or one crash diet, or one trending workout). It's all of the little things that you do day after day, week after week, month after month and year after year that hollows out the stone. 

And you either will or you won't do those things. If you won't, or don't feel like you can, perhaps it's not the nutrition plan or the workout regime that needs work this new year. Perhaps it's the internal work of knowing thyself (Socrates) and building your skills in grit, resilience and mindset.

This is how people like us focus on improving health at Move Daily Fitness. We show up for ourselves day after day and keep the faucet dripping.

I was really surprised by this research! This week I did a coaching call in my membership on how to build maximal glute strength. I referenced a study in PubMed that took 17 untrained participants and split them into 2 groups: 1/2 squat group (bending to 90 degrees), and the full squat group (deep knee bend to 140 degrees). 

They measured muscle hypertrophy using an MRI at the start, and the end of the 10 week study. 

Regarding the adductor muscles, both squats were able to increase hypertrophy. However, the full squats were able to induce significantly more growth than the half squats. 6% versus 3%! 

Now, I know a lot of you are going to say that you can’t squat that low because it hurts your knees. Of course, there are exercises that are superior for glute development, such as the hip thrust, and there are some great exercises for the inner thighs as well that don’t require that deep bend. So do what works for you . As for me, I will be adding more of these into my leg days!

Triceps workout! A lot of people ask me how to target the bat wing area. I am assuming they mean the back of the arm, which hosts our tricep muscle. Therefore, tricep exercises will be what you need to focus on in order to build muscle and increase strength in that area. 

Now, in order for that muscle to show itsself, and for the arm not to appear larger, carrying a lower percentage of body, fat would be the key. If you just train the triceps to increase muscle and strength, but don’t work on reducing your overall body fat, your arm may just appear larger. Most people don’t want that, so be sure to have your nutrition dialled in as well for that overall sculpted look and visible muscle tissue. 

This would certainly be an advanced workout as it is focussing on one muscle group, the triceps. This is a lot of time and tension for one muscle. Another good idea would be to take some of these exercises and add them to a full upper body workout. Or even to target chest while doing triceps. That breaks up the intensity a little but still allows you to get more volume on the back of the arm.

I will say this with a caveat, because I know that we are all at different levels, but the amount of people who lead with the phrase, “I can’t do that because…” is staggering!

I read thousands of comments each week, so I know what I’m saying when I tell you there is a difference in mindset. There are certain women who find a way around things that they can’t do and they come up with a solution instead of leading with I can’t. Then there are others who will spew forth that statement and remain stuck. 

If you say, “I can’t” in fitness, I wonder where else do you say that in your life? Pay attention to your words, and instead of talking yourself out next time, talk yourself in!

How do you decrease fat in a specific area on your body? A lot of us have those trouble spots where we are looking to decrease the amount of fat there. As I said, my answer is that the key to that is to reduce your overall body fat percentage. You can’t pick and choose the areas that you want to reduce the fat in however, if you reduce your overall body fat percentage, chances are the trouble spot will also reduce somewhat. Secondly, it’s important to build muscle in those areas as well. As we decrease overall body fat and increase lean muscle tissue, your body composition will shift, and you will have a more sculpted look. Now, it really is important to try and not lose body fat too quickly. You will run the risk of also losing a lot of lean muscle. So eating adequate protein for your body, and incorporating regular resistance training and workouts like this, is the key!

This book starts off with a very interesting study on female caregivers of sick or terminally ill children. I don’t think I can even imagine the stress one would feel in that position. 

The study was aimed at observing what a chronic stress filled environment does to telomere length.  Telomeres, by the way, are caps at the end of our chromosomes. Shortened telomeres can lead to prematurely ageing immune cells, which means worse immune function.

There were many caregivers who had shortened telomeres due to this chronic stress. However, they did observe some who had longer telomeres. So, of course, they had to observe these women more closely to see what was causing this difference.

What they found was that mothers who perceived themselves to be under the most stress were  the ones with the shortest telomeres. 

Even though the women had the same type of stress, they differed in their stress response.

People tend to have many thoughts and feelings when facing a stressful situation. Here are two different types of responses: One is characterized by feeling threatened, by a fear of losing, or possibly being shamed. The other is characterized by feeling challenged and confident about achieving a positive outcome. Pg. 85 

Food for thought when facing your next stressful moment. 💙

Fasting versus frequent meals: which one yeilds better fat loss results for women over 40?
I just answered a similar question over in the membership, so I thought I would put my two cents in over here as well. Feel free to comment below!
Intermittent fasting or TRE (time restricted eating) can be a very beneficial strategy for fat loss. Typically people eat in an 8 hour window and fast for a 16 hour window. By virtue of restricting your eating time, you just aren't as likely to consume as many calories as if you allotted yourself 16 hours to eat. In menopause this is even more ideal.
During menopause, estrogen levels decline significantly in women. This decline can contribute to decreased insulin sensitivity and an increased risk of insulin resistance. Insulin resistance makes it harder for cells to respond to insulin, resulting in higher blood sugar levels. The hormonal changes during menopause can be a contributing factor to the increased incidence of insulin resistance and type 2 diabetes in postmenopausal women. Therefore, preventing constant glucose spikes is important! Fasting does this well.
Here's the possible downside: Are you able to eat an adequate amount of protein (or fuel for that matter) in a shortened eating window? If your top target is to build lean muscle tissue (which is crucial as we (then you know it is ideal to consume between 1.6-2.2 grams of protein/kg of body weight.
For me personally, that means between 96-124 grams of protein per day. At the low end, that's 3 meals with 30 grams, which is doable. However, if I want to reach that top end to optimize growth, I can't possibly eat that amount in only 8 hours. So then, the frequent smaller meals might be a better strategy for me.
When trying to grow muscle, you want to be in that anabolic window more frequently throughout the day. You want to be feeding the muscle, and not in a catabolic state (which is what we are in during IF).
Smaller meals, where your protein is spread throughout the day can be a more efficient way of building lean mass, while reducing your body fat %.

I know this subject of whether or not you can spot train specific areas is heated and so I debated even posting this video. 

But when I read this study. I thought that it made sense. I’ve also heard Dr. Andrew Huberman talk about mobilizing and oxidizing fat pads by increasing the amount of exercises that you do on a specific part. 
 
So when I read through this study, and saw that Menno said “ the mechanism that leads to this results is that local fat mobilization due to higher temperature in the exercised body parts at high training intensities, followed by oxidation during the endurance exercise” I found that interesting. 

The study was done in untrained females, so that’s a huge consideration as well. When we go from doing nothing to doing something, we are going to see some good results. 

I still think a reduction in your overall body fat percentage is going to be the key if you want to see a reduction of fat in a specific area. It might be the very last place your body loses fat, but if you carry a low enough body fat percentage, that area will likely reduce. Another big consideration though, is what it takes to have a lower body fat percentage and are you willing to do that? There is always a cost and for many of us that cost is too great or we don’t care enough.

anyway, food for thought. I think the most important thing is that we are just moving daily and doing our best to optimize our health!
